Here are some useful links to gain more background knowledge of stylometry and attribution methods:

Extensive documentation for “stylo” package

R language and stylo

stylo is the major stylometry tool with user interface which is both simple to use and efficient (tuning parameters, transparent in input/output data)

stylo runs inside the R programming language, so if you want to use it on your own system you would need to install R
R for different OS

After getting the core R you would probably want to install RStudio - essential environment for the language (makes things really easier)
RStudio

R tutorial

For those who use R and programming languages for the first time it could be useful to play with some basic code: for example this one, adapted by Peeter Tiinits from David Lorenz.

Working directories and projects

When using RStudio you need to create new project (menu is available when you run RStudio for the first time or under File -> New Project… bar)

This will create and set new working space in the folder of your choice. Think of it as the master folder which R will be referencing for external files and also saving your work and data there.

To check your current working directory/project folder run

getwd()

Executing code

By default in RStudio you have an editor panel on the top (File -> New File -> R Script to create new script) and a console on the bottom.

Editor is like a notepad. You can write your code there and it will stay there. You can execute code from your editor by selecting the code you want to run and pressing the Run button. You can do the same by pressing Ctrl + Enter: R will execute selected code (or code that is marked by a cursor).

Executing code

The Console is the heart and engine of R. This is where your code actually runs and this is the place where you can see output of your commands. You can go and feed commands directly to the console. Note that you can execute only one line at a time.

stylo package

First you need to install the package stylo as it doesn’t come with R by default

install.packages("stylo")

Once you have it installed in your system, you don’t need to reinstall it every time!

Load the library in memory (you would need to do that every time you reopen the script/project)

library("stylo"")

Main functions

We will cover here four main functions from the stylo package

  • stylo() - main explorative tool that computes distances between given set of texts and performs further visualization;
  • classify() - machine learning classification of set of texts against the training corpus;
  • rolling.classify() - a method to attribute sequential overlapping chunks of one text to training corpus classes / authors;
  • oppose() - finding most distinctive words between two sets of texts using zeta-scores method;

stylo()

By default stylo() function goes to

.../WORKING_DIRECTORY/corpus

to get the texts for analysis. So make sure you have a folder named corpus inside your project/working folder. You need to place texts for analysis in this /corpus folder.

Then you can simply run the plain function and stylo GUI should appear in the pop-up window

stylo()

NB Sometimes Mac users will experience XQuartz error and GUI won’t open. It should be easily fixable with installing XQuartz package.

stylo GUI. Input

Here you set options for your input format (usually you will use default plain .txt files) and language of texts. If the language is not listed, select Other. Stylo is language-independent and only use language info to cut pronouns.

stylo GUI. Input

You need to check UTF-8 box only on Windows (NB In current version of the package it assumes UTF-8 by default, instead allowing you use encoding native for your files)

stylo GUI. Features

In this tab you define features of texts that will be used for further analysis. You can switch between word n-grams and character n-grams. Note that the default option is word n-gram with size 1: so basically just a word. Simple classics.

stylo GUI. Features - MFW

MFW stands for the Most Frequent Words. This is the amount of top frequent words that would be used to calculate distances. Start at freq. rank to skip the top of the wordlist. 100 MFW that start at rank 11 would include 11-110 MFWs.

stylo GUI. Features - MFW

NB Minumum, Maximum and Increment settings are used for iterative experiments and are only meaningful for Consensus Tree (see the next tab on that). In other cases keep the same values for Min and Max

stylo GUI. Features - Culling

Culling is measured in percents and is controlling the amount of MFWs that should be shared by all texts in corpus. If culling=100 then every feature from a desired MFW set should be present in all texts. All features that do not satisfy this condition will be culled out and not used in the analysis.

stylo GUI. Features - Various

Here you can order the program to use existing table with frequencies and wordlist. It makes sense when you already run the experiment and just want to tweak some parameters (like MFWs, distance measures) with existing data in order to save time on text-processing. Also for custom data.

stylo GUI. Statistics - Clustering

These are implementations of hierarchical clustering techniques used for visualization of final results (the distances of texts between each other). Consensus tree tries to form a consensus clusterization based on several experimental runs (that is why you need increments from the FEATURES tab)

stylo GUI. Statistics - 2D

MDS (Multi-dimensional Scaling), PCA (Principle Component Analysis), and tSNE (Stochastic Member Embedding) are techinques that reduce dimensionality of data and project the relations of data points onto two-dimensional space.

stylo GUI. Statistics - Distances

Calculating distances between texts given frequencies of their features (words) is the heart of stylometry. Here you have various measures for that.
Hint: Safe choices in terms of performance and predictability are classic Burrow’s delta, Cosine Delta, Min-Max.

stylo GUI. Sampling

Here you can make samples out of your supplied texts.
Normal sampling is cutting your texts in sequential chunk of n size each (in words or specified features)
Random sampling is taking n features out of your texts randomly (and you specify how many times it needs to do that)

stylo GUI. Sampling

NB you can save samples that are generated that way by ticking appropriate box in the OUTPUT tab.

stylo GUI. Output

Output options mainly are concerned with visualizations.

stylo GUI. Output - Data

The last row is important. You can save here additional data from your experiments.
Distance table is the final matrix with distances of all texts to each other
Features actually used in your experiment (MFWs)

stylo GUI. Output - Data

Frequencies table include frequencies of all the features (words) in every separate text. Note that numbers here are not absolute, but relative (% of the overall document size). But they are also not normalized. Normalized frequencies are actually used by many distance measurements (and, famously, classic Delta)

stylo output

After each successfull run of stylo() output files are automatically generated in your working directory. They include:

  • stylo_config.txt: the configuration file that holds all settings that you used in the last run (input, features, statistics, etc)
  • wordlist.txt: a list of all features (words by default) of your corpus. NB you can tweak this list how you want and then run “stylo” with “use existing wordlist” option enabled. This will use words only from your custom wordlist
  • table_with_frequncies.txt: relative frequencies of all features
  • EDGES: a comma-separated table for building networks out of your results. The “weight” of links is derived from the “closeness” of neighbours.

stylo output

If you used OUTPUT tab to save additional features you will also find frequencies_analyzed.txt and distance_table.txt.

All .txt tables are separated with spaces and could be opened as sheets (e.g. Excel). Or loaded in R right away for further manipulations:

freq = read.table("table_with_frequencies.txt", sep = " ")

GUI is boring

If you agree with this statement, then you should know that stylo() function can take attributes. gui= controls the popping window, so with gui=FALSE stylo just runs over your corpus with default settings

stylo(gui=FALSE)

How to change that? You may look for attributes in stylo_config.txt (for the most part they are self-evident) and then feed your custom settings to the stylo() function.

GUI is boring

So you can write something like that:

stylo(gui = FALSE,
      corpus.lang="Other",
      analyzed.features = "c",
      ngram.size = 4,
      mfw.min=400,
      mfw.max=400,
      analysis.type = "CA")

This means that we are running stylo with GUI disabled, language is set to “Other” and we are dealing with 400 most frequent character 4-grams (sequences of 4 characters) with cluster analysis as the output.

classify()

When you call function classify() stylo starts to look for texts in two folders:

MY_WORKING_DIRECTORY/primary_set
MY_WORKING_DIRECTORY/secondary_set

primary_set folder in this case is training corpus. Texts from this directory will be used by a classification algorithm to learn differences between classes (e.g. authors) of your data. secondary_set folder is test corpus. Texts from this directory will be used to classify test set to classes that were learned with training corpus. Evaluation will be done automatically based on matching/mismatching labels.

labels

“stylo” automatically derives information about “classes” of your data from filenames. The string before the first underscore is assumed to be a class.

So in “Dickens_Pickwick_Papers_1837.txt” “Dickens” would be treated as class. If you have several texts of Dickens, you would want to keep standart labels so that “stylo” would know that Dickens texts all form the same class.

labels

The color-coding in visualizatios is also done based on labels:

Colors here are not based on the results of clustering but use preexisting lables. If some Kipling text would appear in Conrad’s cluster it will still remain green.

Architecture of experiment starts with your vision of classes of your training data (what texts you want to test against which classes - is it gender, authorship, genre etc.?)

classify() GUI

In general classify() GUI repeats the stylo() GUI: you have control over your input, features etc.

Only STATISTICS tab differs significantly

classify() GUI - Machine learning

You can use distance measures to perform machine learning. Regression algorithm based on Delta will learn differences between your classes in primary_set.

classify() GUI - Machine learning

However you can choose to perform more powerful machine learning techniques that will directly use feature frequencies. SVM (Support Vector Machine) is probably the most reliable choice with high performance.

classify() GUI - Machine learning

NB
classify() function gives the success rate as an input (instead of visualization). This is our goal when doing machine classification: to know how good is performance of a classifier when it is “guessing” classes in the test set against training set and what are misatributions.

You can run big experiments in the loop with gui=FALSE and change parameters of your model for each iteration (different MFWs, sample sizes, culling, etc.).

rolling.classify()

rolling.classify() performs sequential text classification: it breaks tested text to overlapping (rolling) slices and then tries to attribute each slice to the classes in training corpus. Useful for the cases of multiple authorship.

The training and classifcation is performed in the same machine-learning fashion from classify():

  1. learn differences between classes in training corpus;
  2. guess class of the text slice-by-slice

By default it looks for texts in two folders: reference set/ for training corpus (classes to be attributed) and test_set/ (text in question).

rolling.classify()

The function doesn’t have GUI, so it takes tinkering with arguments to run it:
In this example we have two texts of Ward and two texts of Woolf as reference set and Night and day novel (Woolf) in test set

rolling.classify(analyzed.features="w",
                 ngram.size = 1,
                 mfw=500,
                 slice.size = 5000,
                 slice.overlap = 500
                 classification.method="svm")

rolling.classify()

The stripe on the bottom is colored according to classification results (red - Ward, green Woolf). A significant portion of text is actually attributed to Ward!

oppose()

oppose() function is used to find most distinctive words in two sets of texts.
It also uses same directories to look for these two sets:

MY_WORKING_DIRECTORY/primary_set
MY_WORKING_DIRECTORY/secondary_set

Now there are no hierarchical relations between these folders (as in classification task). It’s just a head-to-head comparision.

oppose()

oppose() is based on zeta-scores. It is assigning this score to words in two sets based on their mutual occurence.
To do that both sets are sliced to some equally-sized pieces. Then probability of occurence of words within these chunks is tested. If some word will appear in all chunks of primary set and never appear in chunks of secondary set then:

  • zeta-score of this word for primary set will be equal to 1.
  • zeta-score of this word for secondary set will be equal to -1.

In general this means that very frequent words shared in language will always appear across chunks in both sets and would be assigned neutral zeta-scores (around 0). On the other hand, medium-frequency and rare words with variation in their use across two sets will score the most.

oppose() GUI

NB oppose() GUI doesn’t have an option for setting language; it uses English by default. If your corpus is in the other language you need to set it manually running oppose() with attribute corpus.lang=

oppose(corpus.lang = "Other")

oppose() GUI

Slice Length is the size of chunk that you would use to cut texts. Default is 3000 features (words).

oppose() GUI

Slice Overlap is the amount of overlap between your chunks when cutting texts. So with slice length 1000 and overlap 100, text will be sliced in first 1-1000 words, then 900-1900 etc. This is used to decrease arbitrariness of cuts.

oppose() GUI

Occurence treshold sets a limit for word appearances to be scored. By default only words with frequency over 2 could be scored.

oppose() GUI

Filter treshold sets limit for zeta-scores values. By default only words with more than 0.1 score will be included in results.

oppose() GUI

Different variants of calculating zeta-scores. Original author of the method is Hugh Craig. See his book co-authored with Arthur Kinney Shakespeare, Computers and the Mystery of Authorship (2009)
